    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>

        <p>
            A geometric sequence is a sequence where each term is obtained by multiplying the previous term by a constant called the common ratio <m>r</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
            In some geometric sequences, the terms become smaller and approach zero when:
        </p>

        <p>
            <m>-1 &lt; r &lt; 1</m>
        </p>

        <p>
            In such cases, even though the sequence continues forever, the total sum approaches a fixed value.
        </p>

        <p>
            This happens because the term <m>r^n</m> becomes extremely small as <m>n</m> increases.
        </p>

        <p>
            Therefore, the sum to infinity is:
        </p>

        <p>
            <m>S_{\infty} = \frac{a}{1 - r}</m>
        </p>
    </insight>

